#TuesdayThoughts  Think about why you are going to #InfoSec / #Hacker conferences. Are you going for the social aspect, or do you actually have a 'I learned a thing' from it? If it is for the social, it's basically a vacation, and that's how your employer might see it too.
@nomadicdevop Read exactly what I tweeted after that

@ayeayecapn3 @daveaitel I used to bake it into my employment agreement. Sometimes orgs won't give you more $$ but they will allow guaranteed training/travel to be included (and I used to spell out BlackHat/DEF CON).
@MisterGlass @dontlook @notdan That is a great way to go about things, and easily articulated as well! I love this approach.

The more my personal time becomes limited, the harder the scrutiny I /personally/ put on what I attend and devote volunteer hours to in order to ensure I find value either for personal or career growth. #Conferences

Yes, I personally know the value of social connections. I also want my followers to think about how to not only position the value of conferences but also articulate their take-aways post-conference and how it values the /organization/ that is paying for it.
@MisterGlass @notdan I totally understand that is valid, but how would you communicate what you learned in hallway track to an employer when trying to get the time off/funding for the conference?

@magen_wu Glad that you mentioned that - /Volunteering/ is valid when you are giving up your time/efforts, if your organization is paying your salary and it's not a paid vacation, then you are actually compensated for that time.
